  "prompt": "If space (the universe) is a sphere or saddle shape, then what is outside of that? What do you call the empty space outside that comes after?",
  "response": "The shape and nature of the universe are topics of significant scientific inquiry and debate. When we talk about the universe potentially being spherical, saddle-shaped, or even flat, we're referring to its geometry on a cosmic scale, particularly in the context of general relativity and the curvature of space-time.\n\n1. **Spherical Universe**: If the universe is spherical, it means it has positive curvature. You could think of it as analogous to the surface of a sphere, which is finite but has no boundaries. In such a universe, traveling far enough in one direction could theoretically bring you back to your starting point.\n\n2. **Saddle-Shaped Universe**: This represents a universe with negative curvature, much like a hyperbolic plane. This type of universe would be infinite and open, expanding and extending endlessly.\n\n3. **Flat Universe**: A flat universe has zero curvature and is often depicted as infinite and unbounded. Observational data, particularly from the cosmic microwave background radiation, suggest our universe is very close to flat.\n\nRegarding the question of what is \"outside\" these conceptual shapes, it's important to note that the universe, by definition, includes all of space-time, matter, and energy. In most mainstream cosmological models, especially within the framework of general relativity, space-time doesn't have an \"outside\" in a conventional sense because it encompasses all that exists. Asking what's \"outside\" the universe is akin to asking what's north of the North Pole\u2014it may not be applicable because the universe itself defines the very concept of space.\n\nAdditionally, if we consider theories like the multiverse, there might be speculative ideas about other universes existing beyond our own, but these ideas largely remain in the realm of theoretical physics and are not empirically verified. In summary, within current scientific understanding, there is no \"outside\" to the universe\u2014we can only discuss what is within it.",
